00:00:00,090 --> 00:00:02,880
- This is a hologram that I made by hand.

2
00:00:02,880 --> 00:00:05,190
This is also a handmade hologram,

3
00:00:05,190 --> 00:00:07,200
but as you can see, it was made by someone

4
00:00:07,200 --> 00:00:09,030
who actually knows what they're doing.

5
00:00:09,030 --> 00:00:12,000
Both holograms were made
using the same technique,

6
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:14,550
and this one and this one,

7
00:00:14,550 --> 00:00:17,340
the technique is deceptively simple.

8
00:00:17,340 --> 00:00:20,670
You just make scratches
in a shiny surface.

9
00:00:20,670 --> 00:00:21,990
I made my holograms

10
00:00:21,990 --> 00:00:25,560
on sheets of black
acrylic using a divider,

11
00:00:25,560 --> 00:00:28,170
basically a compass where
both ends are pointy.

12
00:00:28,170 --> 00:00:32,100
These aren't like traditional
holograms like this one,

13
00:00:32,100 --> 00:00:35,010
but these types of holograms
you get on credit cards

14
00:00:35,010 --> 00:00:37,590
are the same as these handmade ones.

15
00:00:37,590 --> 00:00:39,990
It's just that the
etching is much smaller.

16
00:00:39,990 --> 00:00:41,460
One thing that's hard to appreciate

17
00:00:41,460 --> 00:00:44,100
on video is that this thing is 3D.

18
00:00:44,100 --> 00:00:46,770
It appears to hover
below the acrylic plate.

19
00:00:46,770 --> 00:00:49,290
I can give you a sense of
that by tilting the thing

20
00:00:49,290 --> 00:00:52,440
in front of the camera or
moving the camera side to side,

21
00:00:52,440 --> 00:00:54,060
but to really appreciate it.

22
00:00:54,060 --> 00:00:56,280
Here's a cross view stereogram.

23
00:00:56,280 --> 00:00:59,580
If you're able to go cross eyed
until the two images overlap

24
00:00:59,580 --> 00:01:02,700
with each other, it should
pop out as a 3D image.

25
00:01:02,700 --> 00:01:04,950
You know, while we're doing
the crossview stereogram thing

26
00:01:04,950 --> 00:01:07,860
why don't I show you this
traditional hologram as well?

27
00:01:07,860 --> 00:01:09,540
It's pretty cool, isn't it?

28
00:01:09,540 --> 00:01:12,033
And here are those other etch holograms.

29
00:01:14,850 --> 00:01:18,060
To show you how etch holograms
work and how to make them.

30
00:01:18,060 --> 00:01:19,740
We'll start with a really simple

31
00:01:19,740 --> 00:01:21,660
just a floating point of light

32
00:01:21,660 --> 00:01:24,150
and then we'll work up to
something as complex as this.

33
00:01:24,150 --> 00:01:25,950
To create a floating point of light

34
00:01:25,950 --> 00:01:28,560
all you have to do is gently score an arc

35
00:01:28,560 --> 00:01:29,820
into the acrylic sheet.

36
00:01:29,820 --> 00:01:32,643
Now, if I put the camera
here and a light source here

37
00:01:32,643 --> 00:01:36,780
then you can see that the light
glint off the etched line.

38
00:01:36,780 --> 00:01:39,060
But what decides the
position of the glint?

39
00:01:39,060 --> 00:01:42,900
Because look, as the camera
moves, the glint moves as well.

40
00:01:42,900 --> 00:01:44,040
Well, the simplest way to think about it is that the etched groove is like a curved trough shaped mirror.

41
00:01:44,040 --> 00:01:46,560


42
00:01:46,560 --> 00:01:49,470
like a curved trough shaped mirror.

43
00:01:49,470 --> 00:01:52,980
I was gonna try and figure
out how to build a large one

44
00:01:52,980 --> 00:01:55,800
of those so that you could
see what was going on.

45
00:01:55,800 --> 00:01:57,870
But actually it pretty much acts the same

46
00:01:57,870 --> 00:02:00,630
as a shiny tube like this one.

47
00:02:00,630 --> 00:02:01,860
And this has the added benefit

48
00:02:01,860 --> 00:02:04,170
of being able to change how bent it is.

49
00:02:04,170 --> 00:02:07,350
See when the tube is straight,
the glint is always directly

50
00:02:07,350 --> 00:02:10,259
in front of the light source,
wherever I put the camera.

51
00:02:10,259 --> 00:02:11,610
But when the tube is curved

52
00:02:11,610 --> 00:02:13,650
the glint doesn't travel as far

53
00:02:13,650 --> 00:02:16,350
and the same thing happens
with the etch on the arc.

54
00:02:16,350 --> 00:02:18,450
And that's really the
key to the whole thing

55
00:02:18,450 --> 00:02:21,030
because your left eye sees this image

56
00:02:21,030 --> 00:02:24,060
and your right eye sees this image.

57
00:02:24,060 --> 00:02:26,070
And if your brain makes the assumption

58
00:02:26,070 --> 00:02:28,860
that the glint is in fact an object

59
00:02:28,860 --> 00:02:33,060
then your eyes will move so
as to converge on that object.

60
00:02:33,060 --> 00:02:36,030
Just like how if you hold your
finger in front of your face

61
00:02:36,030 --> 00:02:39,840
you'll see two fingers
until your eyes move inwards they converge on your finger.

62
00:02:39,840 --> 00:02:42,090
they converge on your finger.

63
00:02:42,090 --> 00:02:45,240
Then you see one finger
and two backgrounds

64
00:02:45,240 --> 00:02:46,560
and the same thing is happening

65
00:02:46,560 --> 00:02:49,110
with the glint except in
the opposite direction.

66
00:02:49,110 --> 00:02:52,980
Your eyes have to move apart
to get the glint to overlap.

67
00:02:52,980 --> 00:02:54,870
And of course, your
brain uses the position

68
00:02:54,870 --> 00:02:58,350
of your eyes to figure out
how far away objects are.

69
00:02:58,350 --> 00:03:00,600
So if your eyes have to move apart

70
00:03:00,600 --> 00:03:02,550
to bring the two glints together

71
00:03:02,550 --> 00:03:05,130
then that tells your brain
the glint is further away

72
00:03:05,130 --> 00:03:06,480
than the surface of the acrylic.

73
00:03:06,480 --> 00:03:07,313
The opposite happens

74
00:03:07,313 --> 00:03:09,060
when you turn the arc upside down actually

75
00:03:09,060 --> 00:03:12,090
and the glint appears to be
hovering above the acrylic.

76
00:03:12,090 --> 00:03:14,010
If you want to make a more complex object

77
00:03:14,010 --> 00:03:17,640
then you simply draw out your
shape and then create lots

78
00:03:17,640 --> 00:03:20,130
and lots of points around your drawing,

79
00:03:20,130 --> 00:03:22,500
creating an etch for each point.

80
00:03:22,500 --> 00:03:24,270
You'll notice that the image is distorted

81
00:03:24,270 --> 00:03:25,710
compared to the original.

82
00:03:25,710 --> 00:03:27,840
And the distortion of the
image actually depends

83
00:03:27,840 --> 00:03:30,300
on the location of the
light source and the camera.

84
00:03:30,300 --> 00:03:31,260
From what I can tell, if it was possible to have the get a proper rendition of the image, but at that angle you get basically no glint at all.

85
00:03:31,260 --> 00:03:34,320



86
00:03:34,320 --> 00:03:37,110



87
00:03:37,110 --> 00:03:38,970


88
00:03:38,970 --> 00:03:40,560


89
00:03:40,560 --> 00:03:43,830
So there's a trade off, and if
I was gonna do this properly

90
00:03:43,830 --> 00:03:47,760
I would pre warp the image
in the opposite direction

91
00:03:47,760 --> 00:03:50,550
so that when the image became warped

92
00:03:50,550 --> 00:03:53,070
by the viewing experience,

93
00:03:53,070 --> 00:03:56,820
it would undo the pre-applied warp

94
00:03:56,820 --> 00:03:57,960
and the image would look normal.

95
00:03:57,960 --> 00:04:00,457
This is all well and good,
but you might be thinking,

96
00:04:00,457 --> 00:04:03,180
"Hold on a second, this thing is flat."

97
00:04:03,180 --> 00:04:05,250
Yes, it's floating below the acrylic,

98
00:04:05,250 --> 00:04:07,080
but it's all at the same depth

99
00:04:07,080 --> 00:04:09,510
and the drawing itself is two dimensional.

100
00:04:09,510 --> 00:04:12,330
So how can we make this
hologram more interesting

101
00:04:12,330 --> 00:04:14,850
by creating lines at different depths

102
00:04:14,850 --> 00:04:18,240
and maybe even lines that plunge
in and out of the acrylic?

103
00:04:18,240 --> 00:04:21,959
Well, one clue is to be found
in accidental etch holograms

104
00:04:21,959 --> 00:04:23,880
that you may have
witnessed in your own life

105
00:04:23,880 --> 00:04:25,860
like when you've run out of wiper fluid

106
00:04:25,860 --> 00:04:28,560
but you use the windscreen wiper anyway,

107
00:04:28,560 --> 00:04:31,740
the top of that bright line
appears to be further away

108
00:04:31,740 --> 00:04:33,780
than the bottom of the bright line.

109
00:04:33,780 --> 00:04:36,120
Similarly, if a metal
surface has been worked

110
00:04:36,120 --> 00:04:38,730
in a circular motion
like this source panel

111
00:04:38,730 --> 00:04:39,870
then you'll have a glint line

112
00:04:39,870 --> 00:04:42,090
that appears to be
touching the metal surface

113
00:04:42,090 --> 00:04:44,310
at the center of the circular work pattern

114
00:04:44,310 --> 00:04:47,010
and move away as the light
glint moves outwards.

115
00:04:47,010 --> 00:04:49,380
And that's because, well, it turns out

116
00:04:49,380 --> 00:04:51,300
that the tighter the arc,

117
00:04:51,300 --> 00:04:53,670
the closer the glint appears to be,

118
00:04:53,670 --> 00:04:56,190
and the straighter the
arc, the further away

119
00:04:56,190 --> 00:04:57,660
the glint appears to be.

120
00:04:57,660 --> 00:04:59,250
And that makes sense because

121
00:04:59,250 --> 00:05:02,220
if the arc was perfectly
straight at one extreme

122
00:05:02,220 --> 00:05:03,150
well that's analogous

123
00:05:03,150 --> 00:05:05,730
to the straight tube that I was holding

124
00:05:05,730 --> 00:05:07,170
in front of the lights.

125
00:05:07,170 --> 00:05:08,550
And in that situation

126
00:05:08,550 --> 00:05:11,910
the glint is always directly
in front of the light source.

127
00:05:11,910 --> 00:05:13,770
So when your eyes move to line

128
00:05:13,770 --> 00:05:17,730
up the glint in that
scenario, they will converge

129
00:05:17,730 --> 00:05:21,240
at the same depth as
the light source itself.

130
00:05:21,240 --> 00:05:22,650
And then at the opposite end,

131
00:05:22,650 --> 00:05:26,280
if the arc was so tight that
it was basically just a dot,

132
00:05:26,280 --> 00:05:28,620
well the glint wouldn't
move at all relative

133
00:05:28,620 --> 00:05:30,390
to the surface of the acrylic.

134
00:05:30,390 --> 00:05:33,570
So it should appear to be at
the surface of the acrylic.

135
00:05:33,570 --> 00:05:36,600
And so curvatures in
between those two extremes

136
00:05:36,600 --> 00:05:38,730
will give you depths in between.

137
00:05:38,730 --> 00:05:39,563
Here, for example

138
00:05:39,563 --> 00:05:42,690
I've created a tilted
square where the top edge

139
00:05:42,690 --> 00:05:44,490
of the square is further away.

140
00:05:44,490 --> 00:05:47,370
So the top edge is created
with straighter arcs.

141
00:05:47,370 --> 00:05:48,840
The sides of the square were much trickier

142
00:05:48,840 --> 00:05:51,630
because each point along the
line was at a different depth.

143
00:05:51,630 --> 00:05:53,640
So I had to adjust the divider

144
00:05:53,640 --> 00:05:55,800
and change the position of the pivot point

145
00:05:55,800 --> 00:05:57,120
as I went down the line.

146
00:05:57,120 --> 00:05:59,910
By specifying where the
arcs start and stop.

147
00:05:59,910 --> 00:06:02,880
You can have objects that
appear and disappear, depending

148
00:06:02,880 --> 00:06:05,520
on the viewing angle, and
if you get it just right,

149
00:06:05,520 --> 00:06:09,780
that means you can create opaque
objects with other objects

150
00:06:09,780 --> 00:06:14,520
behind that you can only see
by looking around the corner.

151
00:06:14,520 --> 00:06:16,950
Because the opaque square in
this hologram is quite close

152
00:06:16,950 --> 00:06:18,270
to the surface of the acrylic.

153
00:06:18,270 --> 00:06:20,400
In other words, I was
using quite short arcs.

154
00:06:20,400 --> 00:06:22,830
You can actually see the
pivot points that I used

155
00:06:22,830 --> 00:06:23,663
for the divider,

156
00:06:23,663 --> 00:06:26,310
because it's created all these
little dots in the surface

157
00:06:26,310 --> 00:06:29,040
and there are various techniques
you can use to prevent that

158
00:06:29,040 --> 00:06:31,560
from happening, but it makes
the whole process a lot slower.

159
00:06:31,560 --> 00:06:34,140
The final thing I wanted
to try was a hologram

160
00:06:34,140 --> 00:06:37,020
of the corner of a cube sticking out.

161
00:06:37,020 --> 00:06:37,890
This is a lot harder,

162
00:06:37,890 --> 00:06:41,610
because all the lines are
changing death along their length

163
00:06:41,610 --> 00:06:43,530
and it was really mind bending to try

164
00:06:43,530 --> 00:06:45,030
and work out pivot position

165
00:06:45,030 --> 00:06:48,450
and divider adjustment
for every single point.

166
00:06:48,450 --> 00:06:50,700
I also wanted to see if I could have the actual tip of the cube poking out from the surface of the acrylic, which meant having some arcs that were upside down.

167
00:06:50,700 --> 00:06:53,310


168
00:06:53,310 --> 00:06:56,040


169
00:06:56,040 --> 00:06:57,030
In the end, I made a bunch of mistakes and it was so hard to get to this point that I just rage quit on this particular hologram.

170
00:06:57,030 --> 00:06:58,950


171
00:06:58,950 --> 00:07:01,140


172
00:07:01,140 --> 00:07:02,970
on this particular hologram.

173
00:07:02,970 --> 00:07:05,250
So this is as much as you get of this one.

174
00:07:05,250 --> 00:07:08,310
This is actually my attempt
to copy William J Beaty.

175
00:07:08,310 --> 00:07:10,620
He discovered the divider
method independently.

176
00:07:10,620 --> 00:07:11,453
Though he does mention

177
00:07:11,453 --> 00:07:13,530
that he found some prior
literature on this subject.

178
00:07:13,530 --> 00:07:15,300
Actually, he has some great advice

179
00:07:15,300 --> 00:07:18,240
