202
00:08:09,240 --> 00:08:12,810
So one issue you may have
realized with these holograms

203
00:08:12,810 --> 00:08:14,790
that you don't get with this hologram,

204
00:08:14,790 --> 00:08:18,000
is the image warps and bends

205
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:21,720
in weird ways as you
change your viewing angle.

206
00:08:21,720 --> 00:08:22,860
Matthew explained that that's

207
00:08:22,860 --> 00:08:26,370
because actually an
arc is the wrong shape.

208
00:08:26,370 --> 00:08:28,680
In fact, most people
creating etch holograms

209
00:08:28,680 --> 00:08:30,300
aren't using the right shape.

210
00:08:30,300 --> 00:08:33,120
They're all approximations
to the correct curve.

211
00:08:33,120 --> 00:08:35,520
Matthew figured out what
that curve should be.

212
00:08:35,520 --> 00:08:37,890
I won't go into the equations
or anything like that

213
00:08:37,890 --> 00:08:39,659
but look, he kindly sent me this animation

214
00:08:39,659 --> 00:08:42,239
of how you might create the correct curve.

215
00:08:42,240 --> 00:08:44,100
So it's possible to do it mechanically

216
00:08:44,100 --> 00:08:45,270
with the right linkages.

217
00:08:45,270 --> 00:08:48,360
But actually what Matthew
did was create a CNC process.

218
00:08:48,360 --> 00:08:51,720
So he defines the 3D shape
that he wants in software,

219
00:08:51,720 --> 00:08:53,490
and then his code converts

220
00:08:53,490 --> 00:08:55,530
that into the appropriate etching.

221
00:08:55,530 --> 00:08:58,440
The etching is then carried
out by the computer.

222
00:08:58,440 --> 00:08:59,273
It's really interesting

223
00:08:59,273 --> 00:09:00,960
to just look at the etches themselves

224
00:09:00,960 --> 00:09:02,640
because there would be no way of knowing

225
00:09:02,640 --> 00:09:05,850
just looking at this mess
here, that this would pop out

226
00:09:05,850 --> 00:09:09,150
into a 3D shape with an
appropriate light source.

227
00:09:09,150 --> 00:09:11,520
This is a depiction of
Borromean rings, by the way.

228
00:09:11,520 --> 00:09:13,590
So here's a quick tangent about that,

229
00:09:13,590 --> 00:09:14,580
because they're really cool.

230
00:09:14,580 --> 00:09:17,910
It's possible to link
three closed loops together

231
00:09:17,910 --> 00:09:20,760
in such a way that no two
loops are linked together

232
00:09:20,760 --> 00:09:23,340
meaning if you break any
one of the three loops

233
00:09:23,340 --> 00:09:26,460
the other two come apart,
and that's Borromean rings.

234
00:09:26,460 --> 00:09:27,930
What about those vinyl records?

235
00:09:27,930 --> 00:09:29,700
Well, earlier I said that the arc

236
00:09:29,700 --> 00:09:32,070
of a circle is not the right shape

237
00:09:32,070 --> 00:09:35,580
for the etch because it
causes warping and distortion,

238
00:09:35,580 --> 00:09:39,390
except under very specific
circumstances where the arc

239
00:09:39,390 --> 00:09:42,000
of a circle is the right
shape for the edge line.

240
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:44,820
And that specific circumstance
is when the etch goes

241
00:09:44,820 --> 00:09:46,020
in a full circle

242
00:09:46,020 --> 00:09:50,280
and the image rotates once for
every rotation of the circle.

243
00:09:50,280 --> 00:09:52,350
And that fact has been used beautifully

244
00:09:52,350 --> 00:09:55,830
in these commemorative
Star Wars vinyl records.

